  (text "[2]\nIn our design, we opt to have to option to have an external\nbootstrap diode, although that is not required, since the \nMIC4102 already has an internal one."
    (at 213.614 52.832 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid 0da1bb96-1de3-47cd-af05-0aa80ba12ebe)
  )
  (text "[3]\nThis resistor is mainly to limit the bootstrap cap charging\ncurrent. In practice, we'll try to avoid using it."
    (at 213.614 62.738 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid 234c696a-99b8-4803-8d09-25ff568b1e88)
  )
  (text "[7]" (at 33.274 94.234 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid 2d4b40ce-45f9-4514-a18c-70446222d4d8)
  )
  (text "[3]" (at 117.094 52.578 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid 42202fbe-0700-407e-8251-9b006fa7dea6)
  )
  (text "[1]\nIn our convention, the half-brige is seen as follows: LS is\nthe gate signal to the low-side switch, HS is the gate signal\nto the high-side switch, HB is the common point between the\nlow- and high-side switches. The MIC4102 uses a different \nconvention. They call HO the gate signal to the high-side \nswitch, LO the gate signal to the high-side switch and HS\nas the common point. Thus, to clarify, this is the signal\nequivalence:\n\n                            Schematic | MIC4102\nLow-side gate signal            LS    |   LO\nHigh-side gate signal           HS    |   HO\nCommon point                    HB    |   HS"
    (at 213.868 42.672 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid 60661e02-6574-487f-ae8b-0619d2325fb4)
  )
  (text "[6]" (at 32.512 72.898 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid 7274ae6f-012e-4ac5-8bb8-05cb702d8502)
  )
  (text "[5]" (at 32.512 56.896 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid 7eabf2e9-6b96-49b9-9de4-acaa35f4f316)
  )
  (text "[6]\nThis resistor is intended to isolate the LS_EN pin going from\nthe connector. On the board, there is the possibility to force\nthe PWM_LS_EN pin to low or high through pull-up/down\nresistors.\n"
    (at 212.852 94.742 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid 8b3725a2-071b-4846-9e83-61f5e6d669f1)
  )
  (text "[2]" (at 102.616 50.546 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid 8e5b40d9-6281-4470-b10f-b52fe6797856)
  )
  (text "[4]\nThe MIC4102 needs only one PWM to drive the half-bridge. They\noffer the possibility of disabling the LS switch, and the PWM\ndrives only the HS switch. This is controlled by the PWM_LS_EN\npin."
    (at 213.36 74.422 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid a046293c-7794-4670-b65b-7726c8d472df)
  )
  (text "[5]\nThis resistor is intended to help damping ringing on the PWM\nsignal line, especially at high frequencies.\n"
    (at 213.106 82.804 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid a07c4bf5-69d4-4ded-8ce2-4a7ac5f1d4de)
  )
  (text "[4]" (at 14.224 65.024 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid c3483812-a0b8-4cc0-b137-c60003923979)
  )
  (text "[1]" (at 51.816 58.928 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid d9476826-4145-440e-9655-133eba0c1a96)
  )
  (text "[7]\nPull-up/down resistors to force PWM_LS_EN pin."
    (at 213.868 100.584 0)
    (effects (font (size 1.27 1.27)) (justify left bottom))
    (uuid ea7bf57e-8688-442a-b70f-3142310b76a6)
  )

